{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513148"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:05:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12026"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12026","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12026"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.04,0.76,0.06,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4604"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96643"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4604","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4604"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12026"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79278"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"3711"},{"type":"tags","id":"3770"},{"type":"tags","id":"4051"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11637"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6952"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33140"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42700"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45044"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96643"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with persistent bleeding following wisdom teeth extraction performed earlier that day under general anaesthetic. Despite exploration and packing of the surgical sites, the bleeding continues. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. On further questioning, the patient mentions that both he and his sister have a history of spontaneous nose bleeds which are difficult to manage, and his father has a history of bruising easily. Investigations reveal a prolonged bleeding time with normal activated partial thromboplastin time (APTT), prothrombin time (PT) and platelet count.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the prolonged bleeding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemophilia A","Haemophilia B","von Willebrand disease","Immune thrombocytopenic purpura","Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with post-procedural bleeding and a family history suggestive of an inherited bleeding disorder. The laboratory findings of prolonged bleeding time with normal APTT, PT, and platelet count are characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Evon Willebrand disease\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the most common inherited bleeding disorder, affecting approximately 1% of the population, and is typically inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, consistent with the family history described (father and sister affected).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Evon Willebrand factor (vWF) is a multimeric glycoprotein that mediates platelet adhesion to damaged endothelium and also serves as a carrier protein for factor VIII. Deficiency or dysfunction of vWF results in impaired primary haemostasis, manifesting as mucocutaneous bleeding (epistaxis, gingival bleeding, menorrhagia) and prolonged bleeding after surgical procedures, as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilia A\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-linked recessive disorder caused by deficiency of factor VIII. It typically presents with deep tissue bleeding, haemarthroses, and muscle haematomas rather than mucocutaneous bleeding. Laboratory findings would show a prolonged APTT with normal PT and bleeding time. The family history pattern (affecting males through maternal lineage) and normal APTT in this case make haemophilia A unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemophilia B\u003C/strong\u003E is an X-linked recessive disorder caused by deficiency of factor IX. Similar to haemophilia A, it presents with deep tissue bleeding rather than mucocutaneous bleeding. Laboratory findings would show a prolonged APTT with normal PT and bleeding time. The family history pattern and normal APTT in this case make haemophilia B unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmune thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E is an acquired autoimmune disorder characterised by isolated thrombocytopenia due to immune-mediated destruction of platelets. It typically presents with petechiae, purpura, and mucocutaneous bleeding. Laboratory findings would show a low platelet count with normal PT, APTT, and bleeding time. The normal platelet count in this case excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare, life-threatening disorder characterised by microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, neurological abnormalities, renal dysfunction, and fever. Laboratory findings would show a low platelet count, evidence of haemolysis, and often renal impairment. The normal platelet count and absence of systemic symptoms make this diagnosis highly unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["von Willebrand disease is the most common inherited bleeding disorder, characterised by deficiency or dysfunction of von Willebrand factor.","von Willebrand disease typically presents with mucocutaneous bleeding and a family history consistent with autosomal dominant inheritance.","Laboratory findings in von Willebrand disease include prolonged bleeding time with normal platelet count, prothrombin time, and often normal activated partial thromboplastin time."],"references":["Bharati KP, Prashanth UR. Von Willebrand disease: an overview. Indian J Pharm Sci. 2011 Jan;73(1):7-16. doi: 10.4103/0250-474X.89751. PMID: 22131616; PMCID: PMC3224412. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3224412/","Franchini M, Mannucci PM. Past, present and future of hemophilia: a narrative review. Orphanet J Rare Dis. 2012 May 2;7:24. doi: 10.1186/1750-1172-7-24. PMID: 22551339; PMCID: PMC3502605. Available at: https://ojrd.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/1750-1172-7-24","Zainal A, Salama A, Alweis R. Immune thrombocytopenic purpura. J Community Hosp Intern Med Perspect. 2019 Feb 11;9(1):59-61. doi: 10.1080/20009666.2019.1565884. PMID: 30788080; PMCID: PMC6374974. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30788080/","Kn\u00f6bl P. Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura. Memo. 2018;11(3):220-226. doi: 10.1007/s12254-018-0429-6. Epub 2018 Aug 17. PMID: 30220931; PMCID: PMC6132833. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30220931/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79278"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12026"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79278"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T15:00:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T15:00:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4604"}},"content"